title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: working Generalized Linear Models often useful create informative beautiful summaries fitted model coefficients. goal prettyglm provide set functions visualize Generalized Linear Models coefficients performance interactive plots can easily embedded rmarkdown reports separately exported shared stakeholders. document introduces prettyglm’s main sets functions, shows apply . don’t find function looking prettyglm consider checking great packages help visualize output glms: tidycat jtools

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: can install latest CRAN release :
code: install.packages('prettyglm')

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: explore functionality prettyglm use titanic data set perform logistic regression. data set sourced https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic/data contains information passengers aboard titanic, target variable indicates survived.
code: library(dplyr) library(prettyglm) data('titanic') head(titanic) %>%   select(-c(PassengerId, Name, Ticket)) %>%    knitr::kable(table.attr = "style='width:10%;'" ) %>%   kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"))

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: critical step package work set categorical predictors factors.
code: # Easy way to convert multiple columns to a factor. columns_to_factor <- c('Pclass',                        'Sex',                        'Cabin',                         'Embarked',                        'Cabintype') meanage <- base::mean(titanic$Age, na.rm=T) titanic  <- titanic  %>%   dplyr::mutate_at(columns_to_factor, list(~factor(.))) %>%   dplyr::mutate(Age =base::ifelse(is.na(Age)==T,meanage,Age))

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: vignette use stats::glm() build logistic regression model. Currently working support parsnip workflow model objects use glm model engine.
code: survival_model <- stats::glm(Survived ~ Pclass +                                          Sex +                                          Fare +                                         Age +                                         Embarked +                                          SibSp +                                          Parch,                               data = titanic,                               family = binomial(link = 'logit'))

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: function pretty_coefficients() allows create pretty table model coefficients, default includes categorical base levels.

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: simplest way call function just model object.
code: pretty_coefficients(model_object = survival_model)

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: can also complete type III test coefficients specifying type_iii argument. Warning Wald type III tests fail aliased coefficients model. can change significance level highlighted table significance_level.
code: pretty_coefficients(survival_model, type_iii = 'Wald', significance_level = 0.1)

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: default pretty_coefficients shows “model” variable importance. vimethod also accepts “permute” “firm” methods . Additional parameters methods also passed pretty_coefficients.
code: pretty_coefficients(model_object = survival_model,                     type_iii = 'Wald',                      significance_level = 0.1,                      vimethod = 'permute',                      target = 'Survived',                      metric = 'auc',                     pred_wrapper = predict.glm,                      reference_class = 0)

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: pretty_relativities() create plot desired model variable. different plot generated depending class variable.

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: model relativity transform model estimate. default pretty_relativities() uses ‘exp(estimate)-1’ useful GLM’s use log logit link function. term ‘relativity’ times referred “odds-ratio” “Likelihood”. can customize label relativity_label input.

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: categorical variables pretty_relativities() creates interactive duel axis plot, plots fitted relativity one y axis, number records category y axis.

title: prettyglm: Beautiful Visualisations for Generalized Linear Models
text: default one_way_ave uses . like use one_way_ave another model type (compatible predict.glm), provide modified predictions, one_way_ave allows custom prediction function. function must return data.frame two columns: “Actual_Values” “Predicted_Values”.
code: # Custom Predict Function and facet a_custom_predict_function <- function(target, model_object, dataset){   dataset <- base::as.data.frame(dataset)   Actual_Values <- dplyr::pull(dplyr::select(dataset, tidyselect::all_of(c(target))))   if(class(Actual_Values) == 'factor'){     Actual_Values <- base::as.numeric(as.character(Actual_Values))   }   Predicted_Values <- base::as.numeric(stats::predict(model_object, dataset, type='response'))    to_return <-  base::data.frame(Actual_Values = Actual_Values,                                  Predicted_Values = Predicted_Values)    to_return <- to_return %>%     dplyr::mutate(Predicted_Values = base::ifelse(Predicted_Values > 0.4,0.4,Predicted_Values))   return(to_return) }  one_way_ave(feature_to_plot = 'Age',             model_object = survival_model4,             target_variable = 'Survived',             data_set = titanic,             upper_percentile_to_cut = 0.1,             lower_percentile_to_cut = 0.1,             predict_function = a_custom_predict_function)

title: creating spline relativity plots
text: critical step package work set categorical predictors factors. fit spline fit age variable categorical variable understand trend.
code: library(dplyr) library(prettyglm) data('titanic')  # Easy way to convert multiple columns to a factor. columns_to_factor <- c('Pclass',                        'Sex',                        'Cabin',                         'Embarked',                        'Cabintype') meanage <- base::mean(titanic$Age, na.rm=T) titanic  <- titanic  %>%   dplyr::mutate_at(columns_to_factor, list(~factor(.))) %>%   dplyr::mutate(Age = base::ifelse(is.na(Age)==T,meanage,Age)) %>%    dplyr::mutate(Age_Cat = prettyglm::cut3(Age, levels.mean = TRUE, g =10)) %>%    dplyr::mutate(Fare_Cat = prettyglm::cut3(Fare, levels.mean = TRUE, g =10))  # Build a basic glm survival_model <- stats::glm(Survived ~ Pclass +                                          Sex +                                          Sex:Fare_Cat +                                         Age_Cat +                                         Embarked +                                          SibSp +                                          Parch,                               data = titanic,                               family = binomial(link = 'logit'))

title: creating spline relativity plots
text: setting plot_factor_as_numeric equal TRUE pretty_relativities() can plot understand bucketed categorical predictors trend. Setting plot_factor_as_numeric equal TRUE also works interactions like Sex:Fare. Age Fare fit knot point 18 35. fit knot point 55.
code: pretty_relativities(feature_to_plot= 'Age_Cat',                     model_object = survival_model,                     relativity_label = 'Liklihood of Survival',                     plot_factor_as_numeric = T                     ) pretty_relativities(feature_to_plot= 'Sex:Fare_Cat',                     model_object = survival_model,                     relativity_label = 'Liklihood of Survival',                     plot_factor_as_numeric = T,                     iteractionplottype = 'colour',                     facetorcolourby = 'Sex')

code: library(prettyglm) library(dplyr) data("bank")  # Easiest way to convert multiple columns to a factor. columns_to_factor <- c('job',                        'marital',                        'education',                        'default',                        'housing',                        'loan') bank_data  <- bank_data  %>%   dplyr::filter(loan != 'unknown') %>%    dplyr::filter(default != 'yes') %>%    dplyr::mutate(age = as.numeric(age)) %>%    dplyr::mutate_at(columns_to_factor, list(~factor(.))) %>% # multiple columns to factor   dplyr::mutate(T_DEPOSIT = as.factor(base::ifelse(y=='yes',1,0))) #convert target to 0 and 1 for performance plots

title: pretty_coefficients — pretty_coefficients
text: model_object Model object create coefficient table . Must type: glm, lm,  linear_reg logistic_reg. relativity_transform String function applied model estimate calculate relativity, example: 'exp(estimate)-1'. Default relativity excluded output. relativity_label String label give relativity column want change title use case. type_iii Type III statistical test perform. Default none. Options 'Wald' 'LR'. Warning 'LR' can computationally expensive. Test performed via Anova conf.int Set TRUE include confidence intervals summary table. Warning, can computationally expensive. vimethod Variable importance method pass method vi. Defaults "model". Currently supports "permute" "firm", pass additional arguments vip ... spline_seperator Separator look identity spline. input null, assumed features separator spline columns. example age spline 0 25 use: AGE_0_25 "_". significance_level Significance level P-values kable. Defaults 0.05. return_data Set TRUE return data.frame instead creating kable. ... additional parameters past  vi
